",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"bash_progress\",\"output\":\"\",\"fullOutput\":\"\",\"elapsedTimeSeconds\":58,\"totalLines\":0,\"timeoutMs\":300000},\"toolUseID\":\"bash-progress-56\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_016dSsKjCdhqLahEeLDcuRnx\",\"uuid\":\"73d8c5da-c885-4470-8ded-966e60cfecb7\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-18T02:15:34.060Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"73d8c5da-c885-4470-8ded-966e60cfecb7\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2\",\"sessionId\":\"9d47c125-80c3-421c-a4f6-e9ee685a7cf2\",\"version\":\"2.1.44\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/agent-refactor\",\"slug\":\"snazzy-jingling-candy\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"bash_progress\",\"output\":\"\",\"fullOutput\":\"\",\"elapsedTimeSeconds\":59,\"totalLines\":0,\"timeoutMs\":300000},\"toolUseID\":\"bash-progress-57\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_016dSsKjCdhqLahEeLDcuRnx\",\"uuid\":\"73d7e438-fe04-4985-bb14-8c050ac51452\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-18T02:15:35.060Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"73d7e438-fe04-4985-bb14-8c050ac51452\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2\",\"sessionId\":\"9d47c125-80c3-421c-a4f6-e9ee685a7cf2\",\"version\":\"2.1.44\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/agent-refactor\",\"slug\":\"snazzy-jingling-candy\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-18T02:15:35.104Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_016YQM5gLf6FBDB1HDtnhzRD\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_018Drp74dp3kD8tx5maZk5dV\",\"name\":\"Write\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/docs/requirements/agent-refactor/review-01.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 01\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-02-18\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: APPROVE (with minor suggestions)\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nThis is the first review for the agent refactor PR (#360). No previous reviews to reference.\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nBranch `soph/agent-refactor` vs `main`. Files reviewed:\\n\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` - Extended Agent interface\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` - New Event/EventType types\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/chunking.go` - Updated chunking (removed TranscriptChunker cast)\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/registry.go` - Agent registry (unchanged, reviewed for context)\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle.go` - Claude's ParseHookEvent + transcript ops\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle_test.go` - Tests\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/lifecycle.go` - Gemini's ParseHookEvent + transcript ops\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/lifecycle_test.go` - Tests\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go` - Updated hook dispatch to use lifecycle dispatcher\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go` - Generic lifecycle event dispatcher\\n\\nAll unit tests pass (`mise run test` clean).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\nNone.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n**1. [cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle.go:130-131, cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/lifecycle.go:90-92] `CalculateTokenUsage` ignores subagent tokens for Claude when called via `TokenCalculator` interface**\\n\\nIn `claudecode/lifecycle.go:130`, `CalculateTokenUsage` passes an empty string for `subagentsDir`:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (c *ClaudeCodeAgent) CalculateTokenUsage(sessionRef string, fromOffset int) (*agent.TokenUsage, error) {\\n    return CalculateTotalTokenUsage(sessionRef, fromOffset, \\\"\\\")\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe comment at lines 126-129 acknowledges this limitation:\\n```\\n// Subagent transcripts live in <transcriptDir>/<sessionID>/subagents/\\n// but we don't have the sessionID here.\\n```\\n\\nThis means any caller using the `TokenCalculator` interface (rather than `SubagentAwareExtractor`) will get incomplete token counts for Claude. The lifecycle dispatcher at `lifecycle.go:362-377` already prefers `SubagentAwareExtractor`, so this is not a bug in practice -- but it is a confusing contract: `CalculateTokenUsage` silently returns partial data. Consider either:\\n- Documenting this explicitly in the `TokenCalculator` interface comment (e.g., \\\"does not include subagent tokens; use SubagentAwareExtractor for complete totals\\\")\\n- Or having `CalculateTokenUsage` attempt to derive `subagentsDir` from the `sessionRef` path (which it already contains embedded in the directory structure)\\n\\n**2. [cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle.go and cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/lifecycle.go] Duplicated `readAndParse` generic function**\\n\\nBoth `claudecode/lifecycle.go:223-236` and `geminicli/lifecycle.go:163-176` define an identical `readAndParse[T any]` function. These are package-private, so there is no compile-time conflict, but the duplication is exactly the kind of thing this codebase's `CLAUDE.md` warns against. Consider extracting it to a shared location (e.g., `cmd/entire/cli/agent/parse.go` as an exported helper, or an `internal` sub-package). The function signatures and implementations are character-for-character identical:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc readAndParse[T any](stdin io.Reader) (*T, error) {\\n    data, err := io.ReadAll(stdin)\\n    if err != nil { return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to read hook input: %w\\\", err) }\\n    if len(data) == 0 { return nil, errors.New(\\\"empty hook input\\\") }\\n    var result T\\n    if err := json.Unmarshal(data, &result); err != nil {\\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to parse hook input: %w\\\", err)\\n    }\\n    return &result, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n**3. [cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go:12] EventType starts at `iota + 1` -- good choice, but consider adding a sentinel**\\n\\nStarting at `iota + 1` correctly makes the zero value invalid, preventing accidental default-initialized events from being mistaken for real ones. However, `EventType(0)` maps to `\\\"Unknown\\\"` in the `String()` method rather than something like `\\\"InvalidEvent\\\"` or `\\\"Unset\\\"`. Consider adding a named constant for the zero value:\\n\\n```go\\nconst (\\n    EventTypeUnset EventType = iota // zero value, never produced by agents\\n    SessionStart                     // = 1\\n    ...\\n)\\n```\\n\\nThis would make the zero-value explicit and debuggable. Minor point -- the current `\\\"Unknown\\\"` default is fine in practice.\\n\\n**4. [cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go:49-51] `ParseHookEvent` returns `(*Event, error)` where `nil, nil` has semantic meaning**\\n\\nThe interface contract says \\\"returns nil if the hook has no lifecycle significance.\\\" This `(nil, nil)` pattern is well-documented via nolint comments at call sites, but it requires callers to check both return values carefully. The current dispatcher in `hook_registry.go:142-148` handles this correctly:\\n\\n```go\\nif event != nil {\\n    hookErr = DispatchLifecycleEvent(ag, event)\\n} else if agentName == agent.AgentNameClaudeCode && hookName == claudecode.HookNamePostTodo {\\n    hookErr = handleClaudeCodePostTodo()\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis is a common Go pattern for optional results. No change needed -- just noting the contract is clear and callers handle it properly.\\n\\n**5. [cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle.go:246-268] `waitForTranscriptFlush` uses polling with `time.Sleep`**\\n\\nThe 50ms poll interval with 3s max wait is pragmatic and well-bounded. The comment explains the rationale. An alternative would be `fsnotify` watching, but that adds dependency complexity for minimal gain. The current approach is appropriate for the use case.\\n\\n**6. [cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go:541-542] Potential nil dereference on `preState`**\\n\\nAt line 542:\\n```go\\nchanges, err := DetectFileChanges(preState.PreUntrackedFiles())\\n```\\n\\nIf `LoadPreTaskState` at line 538 returns an error, `preState` could be nil. However, looking at the pattern, `LoadPreTaskState` returns `(*PrePromptState, error)` and `PreUntrackedFiles()` is called on it. If `preState` is nil, this would panic.\\n\\nThe TurnEnd handler at lifecycle.go:294-298 handles this correctly:\\n```go\\nif preState != nil {\\n    preUntrackedFiles = preState.PreUntrackedFiles()\\n}\\n```\\n\\nBut `handleLifecycleSubagentEnd` does not guard against nil `preState`. If `LoadPreTaskState` returns `(nil, <error>)`, the method call at line 542 will panic.\\n\\n**Suggested fix:**\\n```go\\nvar preUntrackedFiles []string\\nif preState != nil {\\n    preUntrackedFiles = preState.PreUntrackedFiles()\\n}\\nchanges, err := DetectFileChanges(preUntrackedFiles)\\n```\\n\\n**7. [cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go:114-115] Redundant assignment**\\n\\n```go\\nstrategyName := unknownStrategyName //nolint:ineffassign,wastedassign // already present in codebase\\nstrategyName = GetStrategy().Name()\\n```\\n\\nThe nolint comment says \\\"already present in codebase\\\" -- this pattern was inherited. Consider simplifying to `strategyName := GetStrategy().Name()`. If `GetStrategy()` can panic, the `unknownStrategyName` fallback doesn't help since the assignment happens unconditionally. If it needs to be panic-safe, wrap in a recovery.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- **Excellent design document (PLAN.md)**: The plan clearly explains the rationale for every design decision -- separating events from actions, making transcript operations core, the step/checkpoint terminology distinction. This level of design documentation makes the code review straightforward because the intent is crystal clear.\\n\\n- **Clean interface evolution**: The approach of adding new methods (`HookNames`, `ParseHookEvent`, `ReadTranscript`, `ChunkTranscript`, `ReassembleTranscript`) to the core `Agent` interface while keeping legacy methods marked and grouped is well-structured. The compile-time interface assertions (`var _ agent.TranscriptAnalyzer = (*ClaudeCodeAgent)(nil)`) in both agent packages ensure compliance.\\n\\n- **Thorough test coverage**: Both `claudecode/lifecycle_test.go` (429 lines) and `geminicli/lifecycle_test.go` (439 lines) cover all hook types, error cases (empty input, malformed JSON, partial JSON, extra fields), edge cases (nil event for pass-through hooks, subagent end without agent ID), and the table-driven `AllHookTypes` test provides exhaustive event type mapping verification.\\n\\n- **Proper elimination of TranscriptChunker interface**: Moving `ChunkTranscript` and `ReassembleTranscript` from the optional `TranscriptChunker` interface to the core `Agent` interface, and updating `chunking.go` to remove the type assertion, simplifies the call sites and makes the contract explicit.\\n\\n- **Clean lifecycle dispatcher**: `lifecycle.go` is a well-structured orchestrator that correctly uses interface type assertions for optional capabilities (`TranscriptPreparer`, `TranscriptAnalyzer`, `SubagentAwareExtractor`, `TokenCalculator`). The fallback chain (SubagentAwareExtractor -> TranscriptAnalyzer -> skip) is correct.\\n\\n- **HookHandler kept for backward compat**: Rather than breaking existing code that depends on `HookHandler`, it is preserved with clear documentation that `HookNames()` is now core. Claude's `HookNames()` delegates to `GetHookNames()` for the transition period.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n**Overall assessment: APPROVE**\\n\\nThis is a well-designed refactor that cleanly separates agent-specific parsing from framework orchestration. The lifecycle dispatcher pattern eliminates duplicated framework logic from per-agent handlers. The Event type hierarchy is sound, the interface evolution is backward-compatible, and the test coverage is comprehensive.\\n\\n**Key concerns:**\\n1. Potential nil dereference in `handleLifecycleSubagentEnd` (suggestion #6) -- should be fixed before merge\\n2. Duplicated `readAndParse` function (finding #2) -- worth extracting but not blocking\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address feedback:** 15-30 minutes\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":nul