/entire/cli/strategy/common.go` - Shared helpers\\n\\nVerify:\\n- All references to old names are gone\\n- The rename is consistent across all files\\n- No behavioral changes snuck in alongside the rename\\n- Types/structs are correctly renamed\\n\\nAlso check `cmd/entire/cli/session/phase.go` for the new EventCompaction event.\\n\\nReturn a detailed analysis with specific line numbers for any issues.\",\"agentId\":\"a795632\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01NTeC7VbDrStWQqY75ENwxs\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_016dSsKjCdhqLahEeLDcuRnx\",\"uuid\":\"edb0329d-0902-4d0a-b02a-52833db86647\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-18T02:17:08.566Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"edb0329d-0902-4d0a-b02a-52833db86647\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2\",\"sessionId\":\"9d47c125-80c3-421c-a4f6-e9ee685a7cf2\",\"version\":\"2.1.44\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/agent-refactor\",\"slug\":\"snazzy-jingling-candy\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-18T02:17:09.703Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_011yQREPgRE8jRfYZSnM4ADx\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_012WFYsXAtYAtpma3agsA23N\",\"name\":\"Write\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/docs/requirements/agent-refactor/review-02.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 02\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-02-18\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES (minor)\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nFocused review of three files on `soph/agent-refactor` branch (PR #360):\\n\\n1. `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go` -- Generic lifecycle event dispatcher\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle_test.go` -- Tests for the dispatcher\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go` -- Simplified hook registry\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\n- Review 01 covered the broader PR including agent interfaces, event types, and per-agent `ParseHookEvent` implementations.\\n- [x] Review 01 Finding #6: Potential nil dereference in `handleLifecycleSubagentEnd` on `preState` -- **STILL OUTSTANDING** (see Important #1 below).\\n- [x] Review 01 Finding #7: Redundant assignment in `hook_registry.go:114-115` -- **STILL OUTSTANDING** (see Important #2 below).\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\nNone.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n**1. [lifecycle.go:538-542] `handleLifecycleSubagentEnd` uses nil `preState` without guard after error**\\n\\n`LoadPreTaskState` returns `(*PreTaskState, error)` and can return `(nil, someError)` when the state file exists but is corrupt. When that happens, the code logs a warning but calls `preState.PreUntrackedFiles()` on the next line:\\n\\n```go\\npreState, err := LoadPreTaskState(event.ToolUseID)\\nif err != nil {\\n    fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Warning: failed to load pre-task state: %v\\\\n\\\", err)\\n}\\nchanges, err := DetectFileChanges(preState.PreUntrackedFiles())\\n```\\n\\nThe `PreUntrackedFiles()` method on `PreTaskState` (in `state.go:379`) does have a nil receiver guard, so this will not panic. However, the nil receiver returns `nil` (not `[]string{}`), which tells `DetectFileChanges` to include ALL untracked files as \\\"new\\\" -- every pre-existing untracked file in the repo would be falsely reported as a new file created by the subagent.\\n\\nBy contrast, `handleLifecycleTurnEnd` at lines 294-298 correctly guards this case:\\n\\n```go\\nvar preUntrackedFiles []string\\nif preState != nil {\\n    fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Pre-prompt state: %d pre-existing untracked files\\\\n\\\", len(preState.UntrackedFiles))\\n    preUntrackedFiles = preState.PreUntrackedFiles()\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Suggested fix:** Match the pattern from `handleLifecycleTurnEnd`:\\n\\n```go\\npreState, err := LoadPreTaskState(event.ToolUseID)\\nif err != nil {\\n    fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Warning: failed to load pre-task state: %v\\\\n\\\", err)\\n}\\nvar preUntrackedFiles []string\\nif preState != nil {\\n    preUntrackedFiles = preState.PreUntrackedFiles()\\n}\\nchanges, err := DetectFileChanges(preUntrackedFiles)\\n```\\n\\nThis is functionally equivalent for the nil case (both return nil from `PreUntrackedFiles()`), but makes the intent explicit and consistent with `handleLifecycleTurnEnd`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**2. [hook_registry.go:114-115] Dead assignment with nolint suppression**\\n\\n```go\\nstrategyName := unknownStrategyName //nolint:ineffassign,wastedassign // already present in codebase\\nstrategyName = GetStrategy().Name()\\n```\\n\\nThe nolint comment says \\\"already present in codebase,\\\" but this is the file being modified in this PR. The initial assignment to `unknownStrategyName` is immediately overwritten and never read -- if `GetStrategy().Name()` panics, the initial value provides no fallback because the panic happens before `strategyName` is used. This should be simplified to:\\n\\n```go\\nstrategyName := GetStrategy().Name()\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n**3. [lifecycle.go:402-403] Strategy-specific logic hardcoded in generic dispatcher**\\n\\n```go\\nif strat.Name() == strategy.StrategyNameAutoCommit && newTranscriptPosition > 0 {\\n    updateAutoCommitTranscriptPosition(sessionID, newTranscriptPosition)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe lifecycle dispatcher is designed to be strategy-agnostic, routing events through interfaces like `TurnEndHandler` and `SessionInitializer`. This line breaks that pattern by checking for a specific strategy by name. The auto-commit transcript position update should be handled through an optional interface or within the `TurnEndHandler` dispatch, not via a name-based branch in the generic dispatcher.\\n\\n**Suggested fix:** Add a `TranscriptPositionUpdater` optional interface to the strategy package:\\n\\n```go\\ntype TranscriptPositionUpdater interface {\\n    UpdateTranscriptPosition(sessionID string, position int) error\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen in the dispatcher:\\n```go\\nif updater, ok := strat.(strategy.TranscriptPositionUpdater); ok && newTranscriptPosition > 0 {\\n    updater.UpdateTranscriptPosition(sessionID, newTranscriptPosition)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n**4. [lifecycle.go:88-90] `event.ResponseMessage` silently overrides computed banner including concurrent session count**\\n\\n```go\\n// Build informational message\\nmessage := \\\"\\\\n\\\\nPowered by Entire:\\\\n  This conversation will be linked to your next commit.\\\"\\n\\n// Check for concurrent sessions and append count if any\\nstrat := GetStrategy()\\nif concurrentChecker, ok := strat.(strategy.ConcurrentSessionChecker); ok {\\n    if count, err := concurrentChecker.CountOtherActiveSessionsWithCheckpoints(event.SessionID); err == nil && count > 0 {\\n        message += fmt.Sprintf(\\\"\\\\n  %d other active conversation(s)...\\\", count)\\n    }\\n}\\n\\n// Output informational message\\nif event.ResponseMessage != \\\"\\\" {\\n    message = event.ResponseMessage\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIf `ResponseMessage` is set, the concurrent session warning computed on lines 80-85 is silently discarded. If this is intentional (agent-provided message takes full precedence), add a comment explaining that. If not, the `ResponseMessage` should be appended or the concurrent session logic should be skipped when `ResponseMessage` is set (to avoid unnecessary work).\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n**5. [lifecycle.go:154, 260 lines] `handleLifecycleTurnEnd` is long and has a `maintidx` nolint**\\n\\nThe function spans lines 154-413 and performs approximately 12 distinct steps: validation, empty-repo check, directory creation, transcript preparation, transcript copy, pre-prompt state loading, metadata extraction (prompts/summary/files), file writing, change detection, path normalization, filtering, step save, and state transitions.\\n\\nThe nolint comment on line 153 says \\\"splitting would obscure the flow.\\\" I agree that the overall linear flow is readable, but at least three blocks are extraction candidates that would improve readability without losing the linear narrative:\\n\\n- **Lines 218-263:** Transcript metadata extraction (prompts, summary, modified files, position). This is a self-contained block with local variables that are consumed later.\\n- **Lines 360-377:** Token usage calculation. Another self-contained block.\\n- **Lines 380-395:** `StepContext` construction.\\n\\nExtracting these would reduce the function to ~150 lines of clear sequential orchestration.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**6. [lifecycle_test.go:570-617] `setupGitRepoWithCommit` silently succeeds on error**\\n\\nSeveral error paths use `t.Logf` + `return` instead of `t.Fatalf`:\\n\\n```go\\nrepo, err := strategy.OpenRepository()\\nif err != nil {\\n    t.Logf(\\\"Note: Could not open repository with go-git: %v\\\", err)\\n    return\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIf `OpenRepository()` fails, the test calling `setupGitRepoWithCommit` will run against a repo with no commits. The test might pass or fail for wrong reasons. Using `t.Fatalf` or `t.Skipf` would make failures deterministic and debuggable.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**7. [lifecycle_test.go:477-565] Missing happy-path tests for handlers**\\n\\nThe test file has good coverage of error cases (nil agent, nil event, empty session ID, empty transcript, nonexistent transcript, empty repository). But there are no tests for the \\\"normal\\\" paths:\\n\\n- `handleLifecycleSessionStart` with a valid session ID (verifies `outputHookResponse` is called, state transition fires)\\n- `handleLifecycleTurnStart` with a valid session ID (verifies `CapturePrePromptState` is called, strategy setup happens)\\n- `handleLifecycleSubagentStart` with a valid event (verifies `CapturePreTaskState` is called)\\n- `handleLifecycleSessionEnd` with a valid session ID (verifies `markSessionEnded` is called)\\n\\nThese tests would require mocking the git repo and strategy, which explains why they are complex to set up. The routing table test (`TestDispatchLifecycleEvent_RoutesToCorrectHandler`) partially covers this by testing each event type goes to the right handler, but does not validate the handler's actual behavior on the happy path.\\n\\nNot blocking, but worth tracking as follow-up work.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**8. [hook_registry.go:29] Package-level mutable variable without concurrency documentation**\\n\\n```go\\nvar currentHookAgentName agent.AgentName\\n```\\n\\nThis global is written on line 126 and cleared via `defer` on line 127. Since CLI hook commands run as separate OS processes, concurrent access is impossible in practice. But the variable lacks any documentation of this assumption. A one-line comment would prevent future confusion:\\n\\n```go\\n// currentHookAgentName stores the agent name for the currently executing hook.\\n// Safe without synchronization because hook commands run as separate OS processes.\\nvar currentHookAgentName agent.AgentName\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n**9. [hook_registry.go:24] `agentHookLogCleanup` also a package-level mutable**\\n\\nSame pattern as `currentHookAgentName`:\\n\\n```go\\nvar agentHookLogCleanup func()\\n```\\n\\nSet in `PersistentPreRunE`, read in `PersistentPostRunE`. This is fine for single-process CLI execution, but both should share the same \\\"safe because single process\\\" documentation.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**10. [lifecycle.go:62, 113, 155, 419, 449, 467, 490] Repeated logging context creation**\\n\\nEvery handler begins with:\\n```go\\nlogCtx := logging.WithAgent(logging.WithComponent(context.Background(), \\\"lifecycle\\\"), ag.Name())\\nlogging.Info(logCtx, \\\"event-name\\\", ...)\\n```\\n\\nA small helper would reduce repetition:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc lifecycleLogCtx(ag agent.Agent) context.Context {\\n    return logging.WithAgent(logging.WithComponent(context.Background(), \\\"lifecycle\\\"), ag.Name())\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- **Massive simplification of hook_registry.go.** The old file had ~200 lines of repetitive `RegisterHookHandler` + `IsEnabled()` calls in an `init()` function (which needed `gochecknoinits` suppression). The new version eliminates the registry pattern entirely, moving the enabled check to a single location in `newAgentHookVerbCmdWithLogging` (line 103). The `init()` function and all its associated `nolint` directives are gone. Clean, significant improvement.\\n\\n- **Dispatcher switch is exhaustive and type-safe.** `DispatchLifecycleEvent` at lines 39-57 handles all 7 event types with a `default` that returns an error for unknown types. Adding a new event type requires exactly one new `case` and one new handler function. The compiler does not enforce exhaustive switches on `int`-based enums in Go, but the `default` error branch provides runtime safety.\\n\\n- **Proper use of optional interfaces throughout lifecycle handlers.** The handlers check for `TranscriptPreparer` (line 192), `TranscriptAnalyzer` (line 228), `SubagentAwareExtractor` (line 244), `TokenCalculator` (line 369), `SessionInitializer` (line 140), `ConcurrentSessionChecker` (line 81), and `TurnEndHandler` (line 712). Each check uses Go type assertion idiom correctly (`if x, ok := ag.(Interface); ok`), allowing agents to participate at different capability levels.\\n\\n- **Test for compaction behavior.** `TestHandleLifecycleCompaction_ResetsTranscriptOffset` (line 273) verifies a subtle invariant: that compaction resets `CheckpointTranscriptStart` to 0. This is important because a compacted transcript may be reorganized, making old offsets invalid. Good test.\\n\\n- **Clear event routing test.** `TestDispatchLifecycleEvent_RoutesToCorrectHandler` (line 477) provides a table-driven test across all event types, verifying each reaches the expected handler and produces the expected error for the given minimal input. This catches routing regressions efficiently.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES (minor)**\\n\\nThe lifecycle dispatcher and simplified hook registry represent a clean architectural improvement. The code quality is high overall, with good use of Go interfaces, sensible error handling, and clear separation of concerns between agents (parsing) and framework (orchestration).\\n\\n**Key concerns:**\\n\\n1. The `preState` nil handling inconsistency between `handleLifecycleSubagentEnd` and `handleLifecycleTurnEnd` (Important #1) should be made consistent.\\n2. The dead assignment with nolint in `hook_registry.go` (Important #2) should be cleaned up since this file is being actively modified.\\n3. The strategy-specific name check in the generic dispatcher (Important #3) breaks the abstraction pattern used everywhere else.\\n4. The `ResponseMessage` override behavior (Important #4) needs at minimum a documenting comment.\\n\\nItems 1-2 are straightforward fixes. Items 3-4 are design-level decisions that may need discussion.\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address feedback:** 30-60 minutes for Important items; Suggestions are optional improvements.\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":3507,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":100706,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":3507},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYEjFSRNJaFSqTpQhXT6Z\",\"uuid\":\"b6225368-f9f0-4513-8521-f8c5b92dbe52\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"I'm reviewing PR #360 (Agent refactor) in /Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2. Please read and analyze the following key new/modified files for code quality, correctness, and potential issues:\\n\\n1. `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go` - The new generic lifecycle dispatcher\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle_test.go` - Tests for the dispatcher\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go` - Simplified hook registry\\n\\nFor each file:\\n- Read the entire file\\n- Note any bugs, code quality issues, or edge cases\\n- Check for proper error handling\\n- Look for any missing test coverage\\n- Check 