e of error cases (nil agent, nil event, empty session ID, empty transcript, nonexistent transcript, empty repository). But there are no tests for the \\\"normal\\\" paths:\\n   171Ôćĺ\\n   172Ôćĺ- `handleLifecycleSessionStart` with a valid session ID (verifies `outputHookResponse` is called, state transition fires)\\n   173Ôćĺ- `handleLifecycleTurnStart` with a valid session ID (verifies `CapturePrePromptState` is called, strategy setup happens)\\n   174Ôćĺ- `handleLifecycleSubagentStart` with a valid event (verifies `CapturePreTaskState` is called)\\n   175Ôćĺ- `handleLifecycleSessionEnd` with a valid session ID (verifies `markSessionEnded` is called)\\n   176Ôćĺ\\n   177ÔćĺThese tests would require mocking the git repo and strategy, which explains why they are complex to set up. The routing table test (`TestDispatchLifecycleEvent_RoutesToCorrectHandler`) partially covers this by testing each event type goes to the right handler, but does not validate the handler's actual behavior on the happy path.\\n   178Ôćĺ\\n   179ÔćĺNot blocking, but worth tracking as follow-up work.\\n   180Ôćĺ\\n   181Ôćĺ---\\n   182Ôćĺ\\n   183Ôćĺ**8. [hook_registry.go:29] Package-level mutable variable without concurrency documentation**\\n   184Ôćĺ\\n   185Ôćĺ```go\\n   186Ôćĺvar currentHookAgentName agent.AgentName\\n   187Ôćĺ```\\n   188Ôćĺ\\n   189ÔćĺThis global is written on line 126 and cleared via `defer` on line 127. Since CLI hook commands run as separate OS processes, concurrent access is impossible in practice. But the variable lacks any documentation of this assumption. A one-line comment would prevent future confusion:\\n   190Ôćĺ\\n   191Ôćĺ```go\\n   192Ôćĺ// currentHookAgentName stores the agent name for the currently executing hook.\\n   193Ôćĺ// Safe without synchronization because hook commands run as separate OS processes.\\n   194Ôćĺvar currentHookAgentName agent.AgentName\\n   195Ôćĺ```\\n   196Ôćĺ\\n   197Ôćĺ---\\n   198Ôćĺ\\n   199Ôćĺ**9. [hook_registry.go:24] `agentHookLogCleanup` also a package-level mutable**\\n   200Ôćĺ\\n   201ÔćĺSame pattern as `currentHookAgentName`:\\n   202Ôćĺ\\n   203Ôćĺ```go\\n   204Ôćĺvar agentHookLogCleanup func()\\n   205Ôćĺ```\\n   206Ôćĺ\\n   207ÔćĺSet in `PersistentPreRunE`, read in `PersistentPostRunE`. This is fine for single-process CLI execution, but both should share the same \\\"safe because single process\\\" documentation.\\n   208Ôćĺ\\n   209Ôćĺ---\\n   210Ôćĺ\\n   211Ôćĺ**10. [lifecycle.go:62, 113, 155, 419, 449, 467, 490] Repeated logging context creation**\\n   212Ôćĺ\\n   213ÔćĺEvery handler begins with:\\n   214Ôćĺ```go\\n   215ÔćĺlogCtx := logging.WithAgent(logging.WithComponent(context.Background(), \\\"lifecycle\\\"), ag.Name())\\n   216Ôćĺlogging.Info(logCtx, \\\"event-name\\\", ...)\\n   217Ôćĺ```\\n   218Ôćĺ\\n   219ÔćĺA small helper would reduce repetition:\\n   220Ôćĺ\\n   221Ôćĺ```go\\n   222Ôćĺfunc lifecycleLogCtx(ag agent.Agent) context.Context {\\n   223Ôćĺ    return logging.WithAgent(logging.WithComponent(context.Background(), \\\"lifecycle\\\"), ag.Name())\\n   224Ôćĺ}\\n   225Ôćĺ```\\n   226Ôćĺ\\n   227Ôćĺ### Praise\\n   228Ôćĺ\\n   229Ôćĺ- **Massive simplification of hook_registry.go.** The old file had ~200 lines of repetitive `RegisterHookHandler` + `IsEnabled()` calls in an `init()` function (which needed `gochecknoinits` suppression). The new version eliminates the registry pattern entirely, moving the enabled check to a single location in `newAgentHookVerbCmdWithLogging` (line 103). The `init()` function and all its associated `nolint` directives are gone. Clean, significant improvement.\\n   230Ôćĺ\\n   231Ôćĺ- **Dispatcher switch is exhaustive and type-safe.** `DispatchLifecycleEvent` at lines 39-57 handles all 7 event types with a `default` that returns an error for unknown types. Adding a new event type requires exactly one new `case` and one new handler function. The compiler does not enforce exhaustive switches on `int`-based enums in Go, but the `default` error branch provides runtime safety.\\n   232Ôćĺ\\n   233Ôćĺ- **Proper use of optional interfaces throughout lifecycle handlers.** The handlers check for `TranscriptPreparer` (line 192), `TranscriptAnalyzer` (line 228), `SubagentAwareExtractor` (line 244), `TokenCalculator` (line 369), `SessionInitializer` (line 140), `ConcurrentSessionChecker` (line 81), and `TurnEndHandler` (line 712). Each check uses Go type assertion idiom correctly (`if x, ok := ag.(Interface); ok`), allowing agents to participate at different capability levels.\\n   234Ôćĺ\\n   235Ôćĺ- **Test for compaction behavior.** `TestHandleLifecycleCompaction_ResetsTranscriptOffset` (line 273) verifies a subtle invariant: that compaction resets `CheckpointTranscriptStart` to 0. This is important because a compacted transcript may be reorganized, making old offsets invalid. Good test.\\n   236Ôćĺ\\n   237Ôćĺ- **Clear event routing test.** `TestDispatchLifecycleEvent_RoutesToCorrectHandler` (line 477) provides a table-driven test across all event types, verifying each reaches the expected handler and produces the expected error for the given minimal input. This catches routing regressions efficiently.\\n   238Ôćĺ\\n   239Ôćĺ## Summary\\n   240Ôćĺ\\n   241Ôćĺ**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES (minor)**\\n   242Ôćĺ\\n   243ÔćĺThe lifecycle dispatcher and simplified hook registry represent a clean architectural improvement. The code quality is high overall, with good use of Go interfaces, sensible error handling, and clear separation of concerns between agents (parsing) and framework (orchestration).\\n   244Ôćĺ\\n   245Ôćĺ**Key concerns:**\\n   246Ôćĺ\\n   247Ôćĺ1. The `preState` nil handling inconsistency between `handleLifecycleSubagentEnd` and `handleLifecycleTurnEnd` (Important #1) should be made consistent.\\n   248Ôćĺ2. The dead assignment with nolint in `hook_registry.go` (Important #2) should be cleaned up since this file is being actively modified.\\n   249Ôćĺ3. The strategy-specific name 